ğŸ§® 5. Subnetting
Subnetting divides one large network into smaller networks (subnets).

Example:

Network: 192.168.1.0/24
Subnet Mask: 255.255.255.0
Here /24 means â†’ 24 bits are for network, 8 bits left for host.

Total hosts = 2â¸ - 2 = 254 hosts (network & broadcast addresses reserved).

If you split /24 into /25:

Two subnets â†’ 192.168.1.0/25 & 192.168.1.128/25

Each supports 126 hosts.

âœ… Used for better security, efficient IP allocation, and routing.

